#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:1
msgid "Associated constants"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.20](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.20-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:5
msgid ""
"You can define traits, structs, and enums that have “associated functions”:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:12
msgid "\"foo is an associated function of Struct\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:21
msgid ""
"These are called “associated functions” because they are functions that are "
"associated with the type, that is, they’re attached to the type itself, and "
"not any particular instance."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:25
msgid "Rust 1.20 adds the ability to define “associated constants” as well:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:35
msgid "\"the ID of Struct is: {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:39
msgid ""
"That is, the constant `ID` is associated with `Struct`. Like functions, "
"associated constants work with traits and enums as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:42
msgid ""
"Traits have an extra ability with associated constants that gives them some "
"extra power. With a trait, you can use an associated constant in the same "
"way you’d use an associated type: by declaring it, but not giving it a "
"value. The implementor of the trait then declares its value upon "
"implementation:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:59
msgid "\"{}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:63
msgid ""
"Before this feature, if you wanted to make a trait that represented floating "
"point numbers, you’d have to write this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:70
#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:102
msgid "// ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:74
msgid ""
"This is slightly unwieldy, but more importantly, because they’re functions, "
"they cannot be used in constant expressions, even though they only return a "
"constant. Because of this, a design for `Float` would also have to include "
"constants as well:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:95
msgid ""
"Associated constants let you do this in a much cleaner way. This trait "
"definition:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:106
msgid "Leads to this implementation:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/associated-constants.md:117
msgid "much cleaner, and more versatile."
msgstr ""
